{"title_page": "Abdullahi Abubakar Gumel", "text_new": "Senator '''Abdullahi Abubakar Gumel''' is a [[Nigeria]]n politician and member of the [[8th National Assembly]] from [[Jigawa State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nass.gov.ng/mp/profile/944|title=National Assembly {{!}} Federal Republic of Nigeria|last=Assembly|first=Nigerian National|website=www.nass.gov.ng|language=en|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> He represents Jigawa North West Senatorial District.\n\nIn the Senate, he is the Chairman Senate Committee on States and Local Government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scannewsnigeria.com/news/full-list-of-senate-committee-chairmen-vice-chairmen/|title=Full list of Senate committee chairmen, vice chairmen - ScanNews Nigeria|work=ScanNews Nigeria|access-date=2018-01-12|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Infobox senator|name=|office=Senator of the Federal Republic of Nigeria\nJigawa State North West Senatorial District|termstart=June 2015|birth_date=April 20, 1949|party=[[All Progressives Congress]]|profession=Politician|predecessor=[[Danladi Abdullahi Sankara]]}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAbdullahi Abubakar Gumel was born on April 20, 1949 and he is native of [[Maigatari]] LGA of Jigawa State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jigawastate.gov.ng/nss.php|title=National Assembly Members - Jigawa State Government|website=www.jigawastate.gov.ng|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> \n\nHe holds a master's degree in Public Policy and Administration from the Bayero University Kano, Kano State. But before that, he attended Kaduna Polytechnics Kaduna, Kaduna State where he obtained his National Diploma in Accountancy before proceeding to Bayero University Kano, where he obtained Advance Diploma in Public Administration and Post Graduate Diploma in Public Policy and Administration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nigerianbiography.com/2016/03/biography-of-abdullahi-abubakar-gumel.html|title=Biography of Abdullahi Abubakar Gumel|website=www.nigerianbiography.com|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref>\n\nAbdullahi Gumel has served in various capacities. He was the Deputy Headmaster of Gumel Gabas Primary School Gumel, Jigawa State (1969-1971), Stenographer at Kano State Home Affairs, Kano State (1972), Senior Accountant at [[Nigerian Television Authority]] NTA Kano, State (1976-1979), Chief Accountant at [[National Party of Nigeria]] (NPN) National Headquarter, Lagos (1979-1983) and Board Member at Nigeria Enterprises Promotion Council (1980-1983), Nigeria Securities and Exchange Commission (1983) and Kano State Sports Councils (1980-1983).<ref name=\":0\" />     \n\n== Political career == \nGumel's passion to serve his people motivated him into politics. In 1999, he was elected  a member of [[House of Representatives (Nigeria)]] representing Gumel Federal Constituency (Gumel/Maitagri/SuleTanrarkar/Gagarawa LGAs). While in House, he served as the Chairman House Committee on Special Duties 1999-2000 and Chairman House Committee on Police Affairs 2001- 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dawodu.com/hor1.htm|title=HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVE|website=dawodu.com|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, he was appointment the  Special Adviser to the then Honourable Speaker ([[Aminu Bello Masari]]) on Special Assignments 2003\u20132007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nigerianelitesforum.com/ng/autographs-and-biographies/89829-biography-of-sen-abubakar-gumel.html|title=Biography Of Sen. Abubakar Gumel|website=www.nigerianelitesforum.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115071713/https://www.nigerianelitesforum.com/ng/autographs-and-biographies/89829-biography-of-sen-abubakar-gumel.html|archive-date=2018-01-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected Senator for Jigawa State North West Senatorial District in 2015 under the platform of [[All Progressives Congress|All Progressives]] Congress. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/resources/174911-nigeria-2015-elections-senatorial-candidates-full-list.html|title=Nigeria 2015 Elections: Senatorial Candidates - Full List - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2015-01-14|work=Premium Times Nigeria|access-date=2018-01-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married and has children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* www.nass.gov.ng\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gumel, Abdullahi Abubakar}}\n[[Category:Nigerian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]] \n[[Category:1940s births]] \n\n\n{{Nigerian-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "Senator '''Abdullahi Abubakar Gumel''' is a [[Nigeria]]n politician and member of the [[8th National Assembly]] from [[Jigawa State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nass.gov.ng/mp/profile/944|title=National Assembly {{!}} Federal Republic of Nigeria|last=Assembly|first=Nigerian National|website=www.nass.gov.ng|language=en|access-date=2018-01-11}}</ref> He represents Jigawa North West Senatorial District.\n\nIn the Senate, he is the Chairman Senate Committee on States and Local Government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scannewsnigeria.com/news/full-list-of-senate-committee-chairmen-vice-chairmen/|title=Full list of Senate committee chairmen, vice chairmen - ScanNews Nigeria|work=ScanNews Nigeria|access-date=2018-01-12|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Infobox senator|name=|office=Senator of the Federal Republic of Nigeria\nJigawa State North West Senatorial District|termstart=June 2015|birth_date=April 20, 1949|party=[[All Progressives Congress]]|profession=Politician|predecessor=[[Danladi Abdullahi Sankara]]}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAbdullahi Abubakar Gumel was born on April 20, 1949 and he is native of [[Maigatari]] LGA of Jigawa State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jigawastate.gov.ng/nss.php|title=National Assembly Members - Jigawa State Government|website=www.jigawastate.gov.ng|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> \n\nHe holds a master's degree in Public Policy and Administration from the Bayero University Kano, Kano State. But before that, he attended Kaduna Polytechnics Kaduna, Kaduna State where he obtained his National Diploma in Accountancy before proceeding to Bayero University Kano, where he obtained Advance Diploma in Public Administration and Post Graduate Diploma in Public Policy and Administration.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nigerianbiography.com/2016/03/biography-of-abdullahi-abubakar-gumel.html|title=Biography of Abdullahi Abubakar Gumel|website=www.nigerianbiography.com|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref>\n\nAbdullahi Gumel has served in various capacities. He was the Deputy Headmaster of Gumel Gabas Primary School Gumel, Jigawa State (1969-1971), Stenographer at Kano State Home Affairs, Kano State (1972), Senior Accountant at [[Nigerian Television Authority]] NTA Kano, State (1976-1979), Chief Accountant at [[National Party of Nigeria]] (NPN) National Headquarter, Lagos (1979-1983) and Board Member at Nigeria Enterprises Promotion Council (1980-1983), Nigeria Securities and Exchange Commission (1983) and Kano State Sports Councils (1980-1983).<ref name=\":0\" />     \n\n== Political career == \nGumel's passion to serve his people motivated him into politics. In 1999, he was elected  a member of [[House of Representatives (Nigeria)]] representing Gumel Federal Constituency (Gumel/Maitagri/SuleTanrarkar/Gagarawa LGAs). While in House, he served as the Chairman House Committee on Special Duties 1999-2000 and Chairman House Committee on Police Affairs 2001- 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dawodu.com/hor1.htm|title=HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVE|website=dawodu.com|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, he was appointment the  Special Adviser to the then Honourable Speaker ([[Aminu Bello Masari]]) on Special Assignments 2003-2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nigerianelitesforum.com/ng/autographs-and-biographies/89829-biography-of-sen-abubakar-gumel.html|title=Biography Of Sen. Abubakar Gumel|website=www.nigerianelitesforum.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180115071713/https://www.nigerianelitesforum.com/ng/autographs-and-biographies/89829-biography-of-sen-abubakar-gumel.html|archive-date=2018-01-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected Senator for Jigawa State North West Senatorial District in 2015 under the platform of [[All Progressives Congress|All Progressives]] Congress. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/resources/174911-nigeria-2015-elections-senatorial-candidates-full-list.html|title=Nigeria 2015 Elections: Senatorial Candidates - Full List - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2015-01-14|work=Premium Times Nigeria|access-date=2018-01-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married and has children.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* www.nass.gov.ng\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gumel, Abdullahi Abubakar}}\n[[Category:Nigerian politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]] \n[[Category:1940s births]] \n\n\n{{Nigerian-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2003-2007 \u2192 2003\u20132007", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdullahi_Abubakar_Gumel"}
{"title_page": "HMS Pegasus (1897)", "text_new": "{{other ships|HMS Pegasus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Pegasus 1899 AWM 302233.jpeg\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Pegasus''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=HMS ''Pegasus''\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship ordered=1893\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]]\n|Ship yard number=718\n|Ship laid down=May 1896 at [[Jarrow]]\n|Ship launched=4 March 1897\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=17 January 1899\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\"Excelsior\"\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Sunk by {{Ship|SMS|K\u00f6nigsberg|1905|6}} in [[Zanzibar]] harbour, 20 September 1914\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Pelorus|cruiser|0}} [[protected cruiser]]\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|2135|LT|t|abbr=on}} (normal)\n*{{convert|2740|LT|t|abbr=on}} (full load)\n|Ship length={{convert|300|ft|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|36|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|17|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power={{convert|7000|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on|-1}}\n|Ship propulsion=* 8 \u00d7 [[Reed water tube boiler]]s<ref>*{{cit book|last=Robertson |first=L.S. |title=Water-Tube Boilers: Based on a Short Course of Lectures Delivered at University College, London |publisher=Murray |year=1901 |page=139 |url=https://archive.org/stream/watertubeboiler02robegoog#page/n6/mode/2up |oclc=5640870 |accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n*2 \u00d7 triple expansion [[steam engine]]s\n*2 \u00d7 screws\n|Ship speed={{convert|20|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship complement=224\n|Ship armament=*8 \u00d7 [[QF 4 inch naval gun Mk I \u2013 III|QF {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} gun]]s\n*8 \u00d7 [[QF 3 pounder Hotchkiss|QF 3-pounder gun]]s\n*2 \u00d7 [[British 18 inch torpedo|18-inch (450-mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n|Ship armour=*0.25in (gun shields)\n*2-1.5in ([[Deck (ship)|deck]]s)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Pegasus''''' was one of 11 {{sclass-|Pelorus|cruiser|0}} [[protected cruiser]]s ordered for the [[Royal Navy]] in 1893 under the Spencer Program and based on the earlier {{sclass-|Pearl|cruiser|4}}. The class were fitted with a variety of different boilers, most of which were not entirely satisfactory, and by 1914, four ships had been withdrawn. They had all been condemned in 1904 but were reprieved and remained in service, with scrapping proposed in 1915.\n\n==History==\n''Pegasus'' was completed in 1898, and in 1899, she was stationed off the southeast coast of America. She was commissioned at [[HMNB Chatham|Chatham]] on 21 May 1901 by Commander Edmund Hyde Smith, to serve at the [[Mediterranean Fleet|Mediterranean Station]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=22 May 1901 |page_number=10 |issue=36461| }}</ref> In June 1902 she was in [[Gibraltar]] for a [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|coronation]] f\u00eate,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation - celebrations in the colonies |day_of_week=Monday |date=23 June 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36801| }}</ref> and in September that year she visited the [[Aegean sea]] with other ships of the station for combined manoeuvres near [[Nauplia]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=14 October 1902 |page_number=7 |issue=36898| }}</ref> She was later stationed at Australia, China, and finally Africa, serving on the [[Cape of Good Hope Station]] in 1906.\n\nIn 1908, ''Pegasus'' rescued the crew of the wrecked French barque ''President F\u00e9lix Faure'', who had been stranded for sixty days on the [[Antipodes Islands]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19080516.2.71 |title=Castaways rescued |work=Evening Post |location=New Zealand |date=16 May 1908 |page=6 |access-date=24 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329032423/http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19080516.2.71 |archive-date=29 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===First World War===\n''Pegasus'' remained part of the Cape Station on the eve of the outbreak of the [[First World War]]. As the likelihood of war with Germany increased, the commander of the Cape Station, Rear Admiral [[Herbert King-Hall]], deployed his ships in order to counter the threat posed by the German light cruiser {{ship|SMS|K\u00f6nigsberg|1905|2}}, based at [[Dar es Salaam]]. On 31 July 1914, ''Pegasus'' sighted ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' leaving Dar es Salaam, but was unable to keep track of the faster German cruiser.<ref name=\"nvopv1 p152\">{{Harvnb|Corbett|1920|p=152}}</ref><ref name=\"memono10 p17-0\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=17\u201320}}</ref> King-Hall recognised that ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' outclassed ''Pegasus'' and intended that ''Pegasus'' should operate with the cruiser {{HMS|Astraea|1893|2}} while his flagship {{HMS|Hyacinth|1898|2}} operated independently to protect the trade routes around the Cape, but on 12 August, the [[Admiralty]] ordered ''Astraea'' to join ''Hyacinth'' off the Cape to escort troop convoys, leaving ''Pegasus'' unsupported at [[Zanzibar]].<ref name=\"memono10 p21-5\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=21\u201325}}</ref> On 23 August ''Pegasus'' sailed to the port of [[Bagamoyo]] in [[German East Africa]] with the intention of forcing a truce so that the port would take no further part in the war.{{#tag:ref|Similar agreements had previously been made with the authorities of Dar es Salaam and [[Tanga, Tanzania|Tanga]].<ref name=\"memono10 p22,28-9\"/>|group=lower-alpha}} When the port authorities refused to agree to such a truce, ''Pegasus'' shelled the port's Customs House.<ref name=\"memono10 p22,28-9\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=22, 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n==Sinking==\n{{main|Battle of Zanzibar}}\n[[File:Pegasus_bouy.jpg|thumb|left|Lifebuoy from HMS ''Pegasus'' in Zanzibar Museum]]\nOn 18 September 1914 ''Pegasus'' returned to [[Zanzibar City|Zanzibar]] harbour to carry out repairs to her engines. In the early morning of 20 September ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' launched a surprise attack on ''Pegasus''. ''Pegasus''{{'}}s engines were shut down to allow the repairs, and outranged and outgunned, was incapacitated within eight minutes, and the captain \u2013 Commander Ingles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.org/lifestory/6899905|title=John Alexander Ingles|publisher=Lives of the First World War, Imperial War Museum|accessdate=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913135340/https://livesofthefirstworldwar.org/lifestory/6899905|archive-date=13 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \u2013 [[Striking the colors|struck the colours]] to avoid further bloodshed.<ref name=\"memo10 p32-3\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=32\u201333}}</ref> The ship sank later that day, with 31 lives lost and 55 wounded.<ref name=\"navopv1 p296\">{{Harvnb|Corbett|1920|p=296}}</ref> The [[HMHS Gascon|hospital ship ''Gascon'']] and Scottish ship ''Clan Macrae'' came to the aid of the survivors.\n\n{{HMAS|Pioneer||2}}\u2014''Pegasus''{{'}} sister ship\u2014later assisted in the blockade of the [[Rufiji River]] where ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' had taken refuge.\n\nSix of the eight guns were salvaged and two, named \"Peggy III\" and \"Peggy IV\", were used in the land campaign until 1916. Of the other four, two remained in Zanzibar, one was mounted on board the lake steamer ''Winifred'', and the last mounted at [[Mombasa]] where it survives to this day outside [[Fort Jesus]] museum. Twenty-four of the British sailors who died in the battle were laid to rest in a mass grave in part of the naval cemetery on Grave Island, Zanzibar; the remaining 14 were buried in the town cemetery, but in 1971 were moved to the [[Dar es Salaam]] war cemetery. The wreck was sold in 1955 for \u00a3500 and broken up for scrap, although large amounts of debris still remain on the seabed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zanzibar.net/zanzibar/konigsberg |title=Zanzibar and the Loss of HMS Pegasus |publisher=Zanzibar.net |accessdate=15 July 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BF9D8Mw1?url=http://www.zanzibar.net/specials/konigsberg_a_german_east_african_raider |archive-date=7 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Patience>{{cite book|last=Patience|first=Kevin|publisher=Kevin Patience|date=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c_fMQAACAAJ&dq=Shipwrecks+and+Salvage+on+the+East+African+Coast+-+Kevin+Patience+-+2006&ei=IIT1SqfyBZWqMrqrrJkF|title=Shipwrecks and salvage on the East African coast}}</ref><ref name=Konigsberg>{{cite book|last=Patience|first=Kevin|title=K\u00f6nigsberg: a German East African raider|date=1997|publisher=Kevin Patience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Adq2PAAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:%22Kevin+Patience%22&ei=QIX1SrjhEIzKNemgtLEF}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{cite book|last=Corbett|first=Julian S.|title=Naval Operations: Volume 1: To the Battle of the Falklands December 1914|series=History of the Great War|year=1920|publisher=Longmans, Green and Co.|location=London|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Monograph No. 10.\u2014East Africa to July 1915|series=Naval Staff Monographs (Historical)|volume=II|year=1921|publisher=The Naval Staff, Training and Staff Duties Division|url=http://www.navy.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/Naval-Staff-Monographs-Vol.II_opt.pdf|ref={{Harvid|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921}} }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|HMS Pegasus (ship, 1897)}}\n\n{{coord|6|8|54|S|39|11|36|E|display=title}}\n\n{{Pelorus class cruisers}}\n{{September 1914 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pegasus (1897)}}\n[[Category:1897 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1914]]\n[[Category:Pelorus-class cruisers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Africa]]\n[[Category:World War I cruisers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War I shipwrecks in the Indian Ocean]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|HMS Pegasus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMS Pegasus 1899 AWM 302233.jpeg\n|Ship caption=HMS ''Pegasus''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United Kingdom\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}}\n|Ship name=HMS ''Pegasus''\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship ordered=1893\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company]]\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship laid down=May 1896 at [[Jarrow]]\n|Ship launched=4 March 1897\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=17 January 1899\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\"Excelsior\"\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Sunk by {{Ship|SMS|K\u00f6nigsberg|1905|6}} in [[Zanzibar]] harbour, 20 September 1914\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Pelorus|cruiser|0}} [[protected cruiser]]\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|2135|LT|t|abbr=on}} (normal)\n*{{convert|2740|LT|t|abbr=on}} (full load)\n|Ship length={{convert|300|ft|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|36|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|17|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power={{convert|7000|ihp|kW|lk=in|abbr=on|-1}}\n|Ship propulsion=* 8 \u00d7 [[Reed water tube boiler]]s<ref>*{{cit book|last=Robertson |first=L.S. |title=Water-Tube Boilers: Based on a Short Course of Lectures Delivered at University College, London |publisher=Murray |year=1901 |page=139 |url=https://archive.org/stream/watertubeboiler02robegoog#page/n6/mode/2up |oclc=5640870 |accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n*2 \u00d7 triple expansion [[steam engine]]s\n*2 \u00d7 screws\n|Ship speed={{convert|20|kn|mph km/h|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship complement=224\n|Ship armament=*8 \u00d7 [[QF 4 inch naval gun Mk I \u2013 III|QF {{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on|0}} gun]]s\n*8 \u00d7 [[QF 3 pounder Hotchkiss|QF 3-pounder gun]]s\n*2 \u00d7 [[British 18 inch torpedo|18-inch (450-mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n|Ship armour=*0.25in (gun shields)\n*2-1.5in ([[Deck (ship)|deck]]s)\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''HMS ''Pegasus''''' was one of 11 {{sclass-|Pelorus|cruiser|0}} [[protected cruiser]]s ordered for the [[Royal Navy]] in 1893 under the Spencer Program and based on the earlier {{sclass-|Pearl|cruiser|4}}. The class were fitted with a variety of different boilers, most of which were not entirely satisfactory, and by 1914, four ships had been withdrawn. They had all been condemned in 1904 but were reprieved and remained in service, with scrapping proposed in 1915.\n\n==History==\n''Pegasus'' was completed in 1898, and in 1899, she was stationed off the southeast coast of America. She was commissioned at [[HMNB Chatham|Chatham]] on 21 May 1901 by Commander Edmund Hyde Smith, to serve at the [[Mediterranean Fleet|Mediterranean Station]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=22 May 1901 |page_number=10 |issue=36461| }}</ref> In June 1902 she was in [[Gibraltar]] for a [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|coronation]] f\u00eate,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation - celebrations in the colonies |day_of_week=Monday |date=23 June 1902 |page_number=10 |issue=36801| }}</ref> and in September that year she visited the [[Aegean sea]] with other ships of the station for combined manoeuvres near [[Nauplia]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Tuesday |date=14 October 1902 |page_number=7 |issue=36898| }}</ref> She was later stationed at Australia, China, and finally Africa, serving on the [[Cape of Good Hope Station]] in 1906.\n\nIn 1908, ''Pegasus'' rescued the crew of the wrecked French barque ''President F\u00e9lix Faure'', who had been stranded for sixty days on the [[Antipodes Islands]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19080516.2.71 |title=Castaways rescued |work=Evening Post |location=New Zealand |date=16 May 1908 |page=6 |access-date=24 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329032423/http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19080516.2.71 |archive-date=29 March 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===First World War===\n''Pegasus'' remained part of the Cape Station on the eve of the outbreak of the [[First World War]]. As the likelihood of war with Germany increased, the commander of the Cape Station, Rear Admiral [[Herbert King-Hall]], deployed his ships in order to counter the threat posed by the German light cruiser {{ship|SMS|K\u00f6nigsberg|1905|2}}, based at [[Dar es Salaam]]. On 31 July 1914, ''Pegasus'' sighted ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' leaving Dar es Salaam, but was unable to keep track of the faster German cruiser.<ref name=\"nvopv1 p152\">{{Harvnb|Corbett|1920|p=152}}</ref><ref name=\"memono10 p17-0\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=17\u201320}}</ref> King-Hall recognised that ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' outclassed ''Pegasus'' and intended that ''Pegasus'' should operate with the cruiser {{HMS|Astraea|1893|2}} while his flagship {{HMS|Hyacinth|1898|2}} operated independently to protect the trade routes around the Cape, but on 12 August, the [[Admiralty]] ordered ''Astraea'' to join ''Hyacinth'' off the Cape to escort troop convoys, leaving ''Pegasus'' unsupported at [[Zanzibar]].<ref name=\"memono10 p21-5\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=21\u201325}}</ref> On 23 August ''Pegasus'' sailed to the port of [[Bagamoyo]] in [[German East Africa]] with the intention of forcing a truce so that the port would take no further part in the war.{{#tag:ref|Similar agreements had previously been made with the authorities of Dar es Salaam and [[Tanga, Tanzania|Tanga]].<ref name=\"memono10 p22,28-9\"/>|group=lower-alpha}} When the port authorities refused to agree to such a truce, ''Pegasus'' shelled the port's Customs House.<ref name=\"memono10 p22,28-9\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=22, 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\n==Sinking==\n{{main|Battle of Zanzibar}}\n[[File:Pegasus_bouy.jpg|thumb|left|Lifebuoy from HMS ''Pegasus'' in Zanzibar Museum]]\nOn 18 September 1914 ''Pegasus'' returned to [[Zanzibar City|Zanzibar]] harbour to carry out repairs to her engines. In the early morning of 20 September ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' launched a surprise attack on ''Pegasus''. ''Pegasus''{{'}}s engines were shut down to allow the repairs, and outranged and outgunned, was incapacitated within eight minutes, and the captain \u2013 Commander Ingles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.org/lifestory/6899905|title=John Alexander Ingles|publisher=Lives of the First World War, Imperial War Museum|accessdate=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913135340/https://livesofthefirstworldwar.org/lifestory/6899905|archive-date=13 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \u2013 [[Striking the colors|struck the colours]] to avoid further bloodshed.<ref name=\"memo10 p32-3\">{{Harvnb|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921|pp=32\u201333}}</ref> The ship sank later that day, with 31 lives lost and 55 wounded.<ref name=\"navopv1 p296\">{{Harvnb|Corbett|1920|p=296}}</ref> The [[HMHS Gascon|hospital ship ''Gascon'']] and Scottish ship ''Clan Macrae'' came to the aid of the survivors.\n\n{{HMAS|Pioneer||2}}\u2014''Pegasus''{{'}} sister ship\u2014later assisted in the blockade of the [[Rufiji River]] where ''K\u00f6nigsberg'' had taken refuge.\n\nSix of the eight guns were salvaged and two, named \"Peggy III\" and \"Peggy IV\", were used in the land campaign until 1916. Of the other four, two remained in Zanzibar, one was mounted on board the lake steamer ''Winifred'', and the last mounted at [[Mombasa]] where it survives to this day outside [[Fort Jesus]] museum. Twenty-four of the British sailors who died in the battle were laid to rest in a mass grave in part of the naval cemetery on Grave Island, Zanzibar; the remaining 14 were buried in the town cemetery, but in 1971 were moved to the [[Dar es Salaam]] war cemetery. The wreck was sold in 1955 for \u00a3500 and broken up for scrap, although large amounts of debris still remain on the seabed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zanzibar.net/zanzibar/konigsberg |title=Zanzibar and the Loss of HMS Pegasus |publisher=Zanzibar.net |accessdate=15 July 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BF9D8Mw1?url=http://www.zanzibar.net/specials/konigsberg_a_german_east_african_raider |archive-date=7 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Patience>{{cite book|last=Patience|first=Kevin|publisher=Kevin Patience|date=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6c_fMQAACAAJ&dq=Shipwrecks+and+Salvage+on+the+East+African+Coast+-+Kevin+Patience+-+2006&ei=IIT1SqfyBZWqMrqrrJkF|title=Shipwrecks and salvage on the East African coast}}</ref><ref name=Konigsberg>{{cite book|last=Patience|first=Kevin|title=K\u00f6nigsberg: a German East African raider|date=1997|publisher=Kevin Patience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Adq2PAAACAAJ&dq=inauthor:%22Kevin+Patience%22&ei=QIX1SrjhEIzKNemgtLEF}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{cite book|last=Corbett|first=Julian S.|title=Naval Operations: Volume 1: To the Battle of the Falklands December 1914|series=History of the Great War|year=1920|publisher=Longmans, Green and Co.|location=London|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Monograph No. 10.\u2014East Africa to July 1915|series=Naval Staff Monographs (Historical)|volume=II|year=1921|publisher=The Naval Staff, Training and Staff Duties Division|url=http://www.navy.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/Naval-Staff-Monographs-Vol.II_opt.pdf|ref={{Harvid|Naval Staff Monograph No. 10|1921}} }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|HMS Pegasus (ship, 1897)}}\n\n{{coord|6|8|54|S|39|11|36|E|display=title}}\n\n{{Pelorus class cruisers}}\n{{September 1914 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pegasus (1897)}}\n[[Category:1897 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1914]]\n[[Category:Pelorus-class cruisers of the Royal Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Tyne]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Africa]]\n[[Category:World War I cruisers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War I shipwrecks in the Indian Ocean]]\n", "name_user": "URTh", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HMS_Pegasus_(1897)"}
{"title_page": "Tuyo", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tuyo\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rodrigo Amarante]]\n| album      = [[Narcos|Narcos (A Netflix Original Series Soundtrack)]]\n| released   = August 28, 2015\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Bolero]], [[Folk music|Folk]]\n| length     = 1:29\n| label      = [[Lakeshore Records]], [[Gaumont International Television]], [[Idol Records]]\n| writer     = [[Rodrigo Amarante]]\n| producer   = [[Rodrigo Amarante]]\n| prev_title = I'm Ready\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = N\u00fa Com a Minha M\u00fasica\n| next_year  = 2016\n}}\n'''Tuyo''' is a ''[[bolero]]'' written and composed for the show by Brazilian singer-songwriter [[Rodrigo Amarante]] for ''[[Narcos]]''{{'}} opening theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6693172/narcos-netflix-music-rodrigo-amarante-pedro-bromfman|title=Meet the Musical Minds Behind 'Narcos,' Netflix's New Pablo Escobar Series|website=Billboard|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2016|author=Romero, Angie}}</ref>  Amarante wrote and vocalized the Spanish-language song, \"Tuyo\"(\"Yours\"), as the opening theme for the [[Netflix|Netflix Original]] series ''[[Narcos]]''. He was inspired by the thought of what kind of music Pablo Escobar's mother would have listened to when raising her son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://decider.com/2015/08/31/narcos-theme-song-tuyo-english-translation-netflix/ |author=Armstrong, Olivia|website=Decider|title=EVERYTHING YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT \u2018NARCOS\u2019 HYPNOTIC THEME SONG (Including its Translated Lyrics)|date=August 31, 2015}}</ref> The song debuted at No. 6 on the Latin Pop Digital Songs around the 2015 series premiere<ref>{{cite web|date=September 6, 2016|title=HOW THE LYRICS TO THE 'NARCOS' THEME CONNECT TO PABLO ESCOBAR'S LIFE (\"Tuyo\" or \"Yours\" is written from the perspective of Escobar's mother)|author=Nostro, Lauren|website=Genius.com|url=https://genius.com/a/how-the-lyrics-to-the-narcos-theme-connect-to-pablo-escobar-s-life}}</ref> and was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]].\n\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|France|88|artist=Rodrigo Amarante|song=Tuyo|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardlatinsongs|38|artist=Rodrigo Amarante|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}\n|-\n! US Latin Pop Digital Songs (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|PtJ6yAGjsIs|\"Tuyo\" Narcos Theme Official music video}}\n*{{youtube|qdQP6RLZBDM|\"Tuyo\" Narcos Theme Official audio}}\n*{{youtube|zNPXnAVyAUA|\"Tuyo\" Narcos Theme Official audio Extended Version}}\n\n{{Rodrigo Amarante}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Rodrigo Amarante]]\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:2015 singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tuyo\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rodrigo Amarante]]\n| album      = [[Narcos|Narcos (A Netflix Original Series Soundtrack)]]\n| released   = August 28, 2015\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Bolero]], [[Folk]]\n| length     = 1:29\n| label      = [[Lakeshore Records]], [[Gaumont International Television]], [[Idol Records]]\n| writer     = [[Rodrigo Amarante]]\n| producer   = [[Rodrigo Amarante]]\n| prev_title = I'm Ready\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = N\u00fa Com a Minha M\u00fasica\n| next_year  = 2016\n}}\n'''Tuyo''' is a ''[[bolero]]'' written and composed for the show by Brazilian singer-songwriter [[Rodrigo Amarante]] for ''[[Narcos]]''{{'}} opening theme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6693172/narcos-netflix-music-rodrigo-amarante-pedro-bromfman|title=Meet the Musical Minds Behind 'Narcos,' Netflix's New Pablo Escobar Series|website=Billboard|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=September 5, 2016|author=Romero, Angie}}</ref>  Amarante wrote and vocalized the Spanish-language song, \"Tuyo\"(\"Yours\"), as the opening theme for the [[Netflix|Netflix Original]] series ''[[Narcos]]''. He was inspired by the thought of what kind of music Pablo Escobar\u2019s mother would have listened to when raising her son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://decider.com/2015/08/31/narcos-theme-song-tuyo-english-translation-netflix/ |author=Armstrong, Olivia|website=Decider|title=EVERYTHING YOU NEED TO KNOW ABOUT \u2018NARCOS\u2019 HYPNOTIC THEME SONG (Including its Translated Lyrics)|date=August 31, 2015}}</ref> The song debuted at No. 6 on the Latin Pop Digital Songs around the 2015 series premiere<ref>{{cite web|date=September 6, 2016|title=HOW THE LYRICS TO THE 'NARCOS' THEME CONNECT TO PABLO ESCOBAR'S LIFE (\"Tuyo\" or \"Yours\" is written from the perspective of Escobar's mother)|author=Nostro, Lauren|website=Genius.com|url=https://genius.com/a/how-the-lyrics-to-the-narcos-theme-connect-to-pablo-escobar-s-life}}</ref> and was nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Theme Music]].\n\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2011)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|France|88|artist=Rodrigo Amarante|song=Tuyo|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardlatinsongs|38|artist=Rodrigo Amarante|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}\n|-\n! US Latin Pop Digital Songs (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|